Just ready for the european football championship here comes my contribution - a football skulpture made with wooden bars(mathematically its a truncated icosahedron).

Partlist

  • 9 Wooden bars OD=6mm, 1 meter
  • 1 Wooden bar OD=16mm, 1 meter
  • Print the Mold given
  • Wood Glue

Total cost of wood is about 8 Euros

Tools: Saw, 6mm Drill, Rubber Tape, Vise

Instructions:

  • Cut the 6mm Rods such you get 90 bars with 10 cm each. You best tie them together and cut 9 bars at a time.

  • Print and cleanup the Plastic Mold. Make sure, the 6mm and 16mm holes fit in size.
    Insert the 6mm Drill into any of the holes such that the end is approximately in the center.
    Now surround the drill with duct tape outside such it cannot proceed any more inisde.

  • Attach the Mold to the 16mm bar such it aligns on the top. Mark the position of the "mold nose" on top of the wood. This mark is "outside" and in between the pentagon vertices. the hexagons vertices are between the other 2 holes. Now drill 3 holes of 6mm inside the mold until you hit the duct tape. Finally eject the bar and cut off approximately 15mm from the bar with the saw. Perform this 60 Times.

Assemble the Football according how it should look like. Watch out
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Truncated_icosahedron
as a template. Be very careful when attaching the connectors to get "inside" "outside" ,"pentagon" and "Hexagon" correct. Its good practice to work regularily with "layers" e.g. first assemble bottom pentagon with 5 bars and 5 connectors with wooden glue.
Regularily give the glue some time to harden, but always pause with orphan bars. So you can best adjust the angles of the connectors.

And finally share your result with us (and of course think about our austrian football team)!

title: Pollin Roulette case enclosure with 9V battery holder

description.text:
I created a nice enclosure for the roulette PCB electronics kit from Pollin (No. 810 163 - www.pollin.de).
You will need an additional 9V battery and a 9V clip to get the kit up and running in that enclosure.

The 9V battery slips in a small rail which is under the PCB.
Small posts in the corners keep the correct distance from the PCB.
A little cutout lets the wire slip over the edge to the underlying 9V battery.

Print at a low feed rate so that the PCB does not sit too tight in there.

Can be printed completely without supports and does only need a bit or maybe no rework at all after printing.

Print speed can be very high because there is almost no need for retraction and jumps after slicing.

title: MPCNC Sharpie Attachment
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Here is a little attachment for the updated Multi-Purpose CNC machine tool holder https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:724999.

You can use a Sharpie Marker or pen or pencil to do the drawing.

You will need one or two 3x6 mm screws and washers plus a spring from the spring kit you can find at Home Depot. http://www.homedepot.com/p/Everbilt-Miscellaneous-Spring-Assortment-SP-9901/100142075?cm_mmc=Shopping%7cTHD%7cG%7c0%7cG-BASE-PLA-D25H-Hardware%7c&gclid=Cj0KEQjwhN-6BRCJsePgxru9iIwBEiQAI8rq80TpgVQ5vZSh9YOtsZPn6ybWt-3CetZ28zel043RhRoaAgyf8P8HAQ&gclsrc=aw.ds

The spring may need to be massaged to make it fit over the sharpie better. All of the springs in the kit were a bit too small to fit over the sharpie but you can bend one with a little bit of effort.

It is a good idea to sand down the ridges in the insert to enable it ride smoother inside the base. I also added a bit of lithium grease to lubricate it.

Place the spring over the Sharpie and Insert Sharpie into the insert and tighten the 3mm screws very lightly, just enough to hold the pen in place. Tighten too much and the insert will not be able to move freely within the base.

Either glue on the top or use some 2mm screws to fasten it.

Attach to the new tool mount and have fun drawing with your MPCNC. You want the sharpie to touch the surface with enough depth to force the spring tension to push down on the sharpie marker or ink pen.

description.text:
This is a guard tower.
It's pretty straight-forward, there's not much else to say about it.

So like many people I have had very little luck in printing PLA with the 2X. I have a very cold classroom being that it's the tech lab and the AC is on full blast most of the time. This made me think cooling the print wasn't the issue. Like most people the 2X would extrude and print ABS just fine but not PLA no matter the brand. When I would examine the faulty extrusion I thought the extruder wasn't gripping the PLA strongly enough and instead of printing an entirely new extruder or buying one of those aluminum ones from China I would try this first. Works pretty well for me. I'm actually pretty surprised it's working this well. The model has both left and right side. The left side has a bit of a deeper cut for the spring but I haven't noticed a difference. I made it wide enough to slide it and not pop out like the first few trys did. It fits very snug you should definitely sand it down a bit but I didn't I just shoved it in so it would stay put. I've just finished 2 6 hours print jobs back to back with no issues and because it's PLA not warping!

Let me know how it works.

Notes:

The make in the picture was printed using a single extruder, by switching filaments part-way through the print.

Printed with black and white eSUN PLA.

I use the following steps and gcode to switch filaments during a print:

1) Pause the print (from RepetierHost, etc.) when it reaches the correct height / layer.

2) Quickly use "M114" to get the current coordinates, and then immediately send "G1 X0 Y0" to move the extruder to the origin in the x and y coordinates. You want to do this quickly because if the extruder is left resting on the print, it may ooze out filament.

3) Remove the old filament, and insert the new one, manually. Clean off the end.

4) Use "G92 E?", and write the E coordinate you got from step 2, instead of the question mark. This tells the printer what the extrusion coordinate is, so that it isn't confused by the extrusions during the filament change.

5) Finally, send "G1 X? Y?", with the X and Y coordinates in place of the question marks.

6) You may now resume the print.

I've learned this from a post by droftarts: http://forums.reprap.org/read.php?262,108164,111577

description.text:
This is a remake of fma's anti wobble system, thank you fma! Three things are done here:
  • The nut block has greater lead screw clearance. My lead screw was binding on the actual nut block. With the increased clearance nut block this is no longer a problem.
  • The anti-wobble system is reinforced, and is considerably overbuilt. This is my preference, it might not be others', but I don't see how it can hurt.
  • The antiwobble system is made to flush mount a standard M8 nut (c.f. McMaster-Carr p.n. 96621A220). I compression fit the nut into the antiwobble part using a standard wood working c-clamp.
    • Hope it's helpful! Thank you open source reprap community!

description.text:
This is an openscad model that prints out a holder for a razor blade at a specific angle that you can specify when you print. It uses a single flat razor blade:

Logan 270 Matte Cutter Blade

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0000AE6BL/

and a bolt/nut that allows for depth adjustments. I just rummaged through my bolts to find one that would fit, but it is probably like an M2 or something like that. It will just fit through the slot on the razor. The nut catches on the back side so you can easily loosen the bolt to slide the blade up and down to adjust the depth.

In the code, set the value of:

angleOfCut = 75;//This is the angle that matters

in the OpenScad file to adjust for different angles. Then just print it.

It uses the threads.scad library for screws that stick out the back that allow you to adjust the distance to a ruler if you need it (I used it to cut the ailerons on an airplane at a constant width). You may have to tap it if the threads don't print well.

I did something like 3 shells and 25% infill.

Note that the geometry starts to break down for angles less about 50 degrees (where 90 is vertical). You may have to tweak the code to get the razor slot depth to be correct.

title: Bot Window for Cold Environment Printing -- SVG file

description.text: This derivative work exists to provide an SVG file for beauturner's  "Bot Window for Cold Environment Printing" (Thing 15375).  Beauturner's thing only provides a DWG file (which includes the rest of the ToM wood pieces as well).  For cutting my panels, I needed an SVG description and I figured that other folks might as well.  Thus, what is offered here is merely the result of converting beauturner's work from DWG to SVG by way of DXF.  And then removing all the ToM pieces leaving only one of the panels beauturner designed.

In beauturner's design file, the panels are shown mounted with the fasteners on the sides.  They can also be mounted with their fasteners on the top and bottom (as I have done in these pictures).  Either way, you can mount them with M3x16 fasteners.  I used some small "standoffs": glow in the dark "melt-a-beads" from my kids' arts-n-craft supplies.
The first file, panel.svg, is a metric SVG description of one panel.  The panel is saved as an SVG group using blue lines of width 0.010 mm.  To use panel.svg with a commercial service such as Ponoko or Shapeways, you will have to copy the panel from panel.svg and then paste it into one of their SVG template files.
The second file, panel-lizard.svg, also includes a tessellating Escher lizard which I lifted from seanmichaelragan's Thing 14544.  Rescale and cut-and-paste to fill your panel with additional fun.  (However, keep in mind that commercial services will charge you for every stroke of the laser -- you pay for time under the laser and more strokes mean more time.)
The coloring in panel-lizard.svg follows Ponoko's guidelines.

comments.text: Dan, great conversion. The extra parts were originally left in case anyone was interested in the layout (as the l/r side and f/b openings are different sizes). With this I am getting about 10-12f degrees warmer inside the bot. With the winter chills, an open front is causing lift just in that area, and I am starting to work out some flexible designs (that are better than the cardboard and magnet I just pulled off the front window. :)

description.text:
This is a case for the Pocket Operator synthesizers by Teenage Engineering. It's designed to print in one piece from a flexible filament like Ninjaflex, with supports. After removing the interior supports with pliers, the whole case can be stretched over the Pocket Operator.

It tries to be flexible enough to achieve a good button feel while being rigid enough to protect the Pocket Operator in a pocket. I think the result is alright, though the current version is extremely hard to put on. I actually damaged my PO-28's LCD slightly while putting it in. Use care and/or modify the design yourself.

I probably won't keep working on this design since it works well enough for my needs at the moment, but there are a few things I'd improve:

• Add some assistance for getting the case on and off- some combination of pull tabs, an insertion tool, or additional stretchiness.

• More clearance around the LCD connectors, especially at the bottom

• Remove the holes for the hang-tab OR add a slot so that it's possible to actually get the hangtab through this hole once the rest of the case is on.

title: 9mm Wide GT2 Belt Idler Pulley for MPCNC

description.text:
WORK IN PROGRESS - NOT TESTED

Intended to replace the fender washer and speed washer, and allow use of 9mm wide GT2 belt on the MPCNC. (I ordered the wrong belt)

Initial test FAILED.
1) Requires ~2mm standoff washer (flattened lock washer and speed/sae washer) between bearing and roller mount.
2) ABS shrunk dramatically, had to re-print with an ID of 24mm to fit 22mm bearings.
3) Raise the thickness (IdlerOD) to bearingOD+4, with only 1mm, it flexes significantly, which will cause the belt to wear out prematurely.

Uploaded IdlerPulleyMK2, Idler OD is 26, belt width is 9.5mm, bearingOD is still 22mm (you can always sand it out if it shrinks)

Printer:

CTC Bizer MK8

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.25

Infill:

100% (shouldn't need infill, too thin)

Place on a spindle, and gently sand the belt and bearing area with ~600 grit sand paper, to give a smooth surface for the belt and bearing.

Use a thin ring of Gel Super Glue on the inner ring to hold it on the bearing.
Made with OpenSCAD, used a bit of one of the Parametric Pulley things on here for some of the shapes. Source included.

title: QU-BD OneUp Gantry Leveling Pulley System

description.text:
The X gantry on the QU-BD OneUp sags noticeably downward on the right side. I didn't like any of the existing fixes for this, so here's my version.

You will need 3qty 8x22x7 bearings and a guitar tuning head to complete this project.

Printer:

Flashforge Dreamer

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2mm

Infill:

40%

Notes:

I had no problems doing this with 3 walls and 40% infill. You may need to rotate the STL files to print better for your printer, but keep in mind these will be under tension so print in a direction that is strong as well. You will need to print 6qty of the pulley bearing side pieces, two for each side of the bearing.

1. Super glue two sides around each bearing, for 3 pulleys total.
  2. Attach parts. This is pretty straight forward, just go off of the STL names (and see my example shot). The Z bearing mounts will replace the existing square ones included with the OneUp, but will re-use the screws. The top pulley braces may need to be drilled out to accommodate your screws, if they are too short to reach the rods. Just drill them out so the screw head fits nicely all the way down to the MDF.
  3. On the bottom left pulley bracket, try to position it (and all pieces generally) in line with the Z rod so the wire travel path is straight.
  4. Tie some type of wire (jewelry wire is what I used, braided fishing line would probably work great too due to low stretch) on to the left Z bearing mount stud, loop it through the pulleys to your guitar tuning peg on the right Z bearing mount.
  5. Tighten until level. I would suggest leveling the bed height based on distance from the counter you have your printer sitting on. Then level the gantry to the bed.
This is all designed in Fusion 360.
